'''Mugetsu Kokuzō''' (牟義都国造) refers to the ancient rulers of the {{ill|Mugetsu Province|ja|牟義都国}}, located in the northern central part of {{ill|Mino Province|ja|美濃国}}.

== Overview ==

=== Terminology ===
The term '''Mugetsu Kokuzō''' is found in the excerpt from the {{ill|Shaku Nihongi|ja|釈日本紀}} citing the {{ill|Jōgūki|ja|上宮記}}, along with variations such as '''Mugitsu Kimi''' and '''Miketsu Kimi'''.

=== Ancestry ===
According to the {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記}}, {{ill|Ōkuchi no Mikoto|ja|大碓命}}, a son of {{ill|Emperor Keikō|ja|景行天皇}}, secretly united with {{ill|Otobime|ja|弟媛}}, the daughter of {{ill|Kami Ōne no Ō|ja|神大根王|1=Kami Ōne}}, resulting in the birth of {{ill|Oshikuro Otobiko no Ō|ja|押黒弟日子王}}, considered their progenitor. Additionally, it is said that the grandfather of {{ill|Emperor Keitai|ja|継体天皇}} married a daughter of the same lineage.

=== Clan ===
The ruling clan was the '''Miketsu Clan''' (牟義都氏), also known as Mugitsu, Muketsu, or Mugitsu, with the hereditary title {{ill|Kimi|ja|君 (カバネ)}}. Some members were later granted the title {{ill|Sukune|ja|宿禰|1=Sukune}}. Marriage records in the {{ill|Halfuri Register|ja|半布里戸籍}} reveal ties to the {{ill|Kamo Agatanushi|ja|鴨県主 (美濃)}}, suggesting that the Mugetsu Clan inherited the role of water management. They supported the {{ill|Empress Genshō|ja|元正天皇}} on her pilgrimage to the sacred springs of Mino and played roles in supplying the court with its resources.<ref>{{Cite book |author=関市教育委員会 |year=1996 |title=新修 関市史 通史編 自然・原始・古代・中世 |publisher=関市 |pages=542-544}}</ref>

== Headquarters ==
The exact location of the Mugetsu Kokuzō's base is unknown, but one theory links it to Izura (伊自良) in present-day Yamagata City, Gifu Prefecture. Excavations have revealed remains of aristocratic residences from the late 7th century and warehouses associated with administrative facilities in the Nara period.<ref>{{Cite book |author=関市教育委員会 |year=1996 |title=新修 関市史 通史編 自然・原始・古代・中世 |publisher=関市 |pages=565-566}}</ref>

=== Territory ===
The domain of the Mugetsu Kokuzō, referred to as Mugetsu Province, corresponds to the later {{ill|Mugi District|ja|武儀郡}} in {{ill|Mino Province|ja|美濃国}}, including present-day {{ill|Seki|ja|関市}}, {{ill|Mino|ja|美濃市}}, and {{ill|Yamagata|ja|山県市}} in Gifu Prefecture.

== Shrine ==
The clan's tutelary shrine remains unclear.

=== Related Shrines ===
Though not recorded in the {{ill|Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyocho|ja|延喜式神名帳|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyocho}}, certain shrines are traditionally linked to the Mugetsu Kokuzō:
*'''Agata Shrine''' (県神社): Located in {{ill|Yamagata City|ja|山県市}}, it is said to enshrine Izimura no Kimi, a Mugetsu Kokuzō.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.gifu-jinjacho.jp/syosai.php?shrno=1773&shrname=★県神社★ |title=Agata Shrine |publisher=岐阜県神社庁}}</ref>
*'''Muge Hachiman Shrine''' (武芸八幡宮): Situated in {{ill|Seki City|ja|関市}}, it is believed to enshrine {{ill|Ōkuchi no Mikoto|ja|大碓命}}.

== Associated Temple ==
The clan's temple is {{ill|Miroku-ji Temple|ja|弥勒寺跡 (関市)}}.

== Notable Figures ==
*'''Izimura no Kimi''' (伊自牟良君): A Kokuzō of the Kofun period and the father of {{ill|Kurubime|ja|久留比売命}}, the consort of {{ill|Ōhobi no Ō|ja|乎非王}}.
*'''Muge Kimi Masurao''' (身毛君丈夫): Active during Emperor Yūryaku's reign, he summoned {{ill|Kibi no Yugobe no Kokū|ja|吉備弓削部虚空}} back to court.
